  <presentation id="workshop-api-ai-ready">
    <date short="2025-12-10">December 10, 2025</date>
    <title short="AI-Ready APIs">Getting your APIs AI-Ready</title>
    <author>Frank Kilcommins</author>
    <affiliation>Head of Enterprise Architecture, <a href="https://www.jentic.com/" title="Jentic">Jentic</a></affiliation>
    <part id="apis-and-ai">
      <title>Are APIs AI-Ready?</title>
      <slide id="ai-integration">
        <title>AI Integration is the New Moat</title>
        <img src="AI-integration-the-new-Moat.png" href="https://www.oreilly.com/radar/integration-is-the-new-moat/" title='Tim O Reilly, Oct 2025' class="fullsize-shadow" />
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: .3em;">Tim O’Reilly  "AI Integration Is the New Moat",O’REILLY, Oct 2025
https://www.oreilly.com/radar/integration-is-the-new-moat/ </p>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-for-humans">
        <title>Most APIs were Designed for Humans!</title>
        <ul>
					<li>APIs are intended for developers, but not to be <em>interpreted, reasoned about, or safely executed</em> by AI systems</li>
				</ul>
        <img src="APIs-were-for-humans.png" title="Most APIs were designed for Humans" style="height: 50%" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
      </slide>
      <slide id="humans-tolerate">
        <title>Humans Tolerate, Machines Cannot</title>
        <p><strong><em>Human Interpretation:</em></strong></p>
        <ul>
					<li>Vague descriptions</li>
          <li>Inconsistent naming</li>
          <li>Wrong servers</li>
          <li>Missing authentication info</li>
          <li>Missing examples</li>
				</ul>
      </slide>      
      <slide id="machines-cannot-tolerate">
        <title>Humans Tolerate, Machines Cannot</title>
        <p><strong><em>Machine Interpretation:</em></strong></p>
        <img src="computer-says-no.png" title="Machines cannot tolerate missing semantics" style=" height: 50%; float: left ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; " class="shadow"/>
      </slide>
      <slide id="findings-from-1500-apis">
        <title>Findings from 1500+ Public APIs</title>
        <ul>
          <li><strong><em>Broken specs:</em></strong></li>
          <ul>
            <li>Invalid or unparsable OpenAPI Docs</li>
            <li>Missing path parameters / broken `$ref` chains</li>
            <li>Invalid examples</li>
          </ul>
				</ul>
        <ul>
          <li><strong><em>Poor consumer experience:</em></strong></li>
          <ul>
            <li>Examples missing</li>
            <li>Inconsistent naming, unclear HTTP verb usage</li>
            <li>Vague or generic descriptions</li>
          </ul>
        </ul>
        <ul>
          <li><strong><em>Security runtime challenges:</em></strong></li>
          <ul>
              <li>No servers or wrong envs</li>
              <li>Auth info missing (outside OpenAPI)</li>
              <li>Stale / outdated OpenAPI Documents</li>      
          </ul>
        </ul>        
      </slide> 
      <slide id="typical-example">
        <title>Typical Ambiguity Example</title>
        <p><strong><em>Agent Interpretation:</em></strong></p>
        <img src="A-valid-but-confusing-path-item.png" title="Machines cannot tolerate missing semantics" style="max-width: 50%; height: auto; float: right; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ;"/>
        <ul>
          <li>It might <em>create</em> an offer</li>
          <li>It might<em>replace</em> an user</li>
          <li>It might<em>partially update</em> a offer</li>
          <li>It might<em>patch only some</em> offer fields</li>
        </ul>       
      </slide>      
    </part>
    <part id="apis-and-ai">
      <title>Making APIs AI-Ready</title>
      <slide id="where-to-start-api-improvements">
        <title>Where to start?</title>
          <img src="api-ai-focus-areas.png" class="fullsize" />  
      </slide>
      <slide id="summary-and-descriptions">
        <title>Readable <em>Summaries</em> and <em>Descriptions</em></title> 
        <p><strong>Improves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>AI Discoverability, Semantic Clarity, Agent Usability</li>        
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Where...</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li style="font-family: monospace"><strong>Objects allowing `summary`:</strong> Info, Path Item, Operation, Response, Example, Tag, Reference, ... </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace"><strong>Objects allowing `description`:</strong> Info, Server, Server Variable, Operation, Path Item, External Documentation, Parameter, Request Body, Response, Example, Link, Header, Tag, Reference, Security Scheme, <em>All JSON Schemas</em>, ... </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>        
      <slide id="semantic-schemas">
        <title>Semantically Rich <em>Schemas</em></title>
        <p><strong>Improves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>AI-Readiness, Agent Usability, Security &amp; Validation</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Where...</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Core JSON Schema fields:</strong>
            <code>type</code>, <code>format</code>, <code>enum</code>, <code>const</code>, <code>required</code>, <code>items</code>, <code>properties</code>, <code>additionalProperties</code>, <code>oneOf</code>, <code>anyOf</code>, <code>allOf</code>, <code>not</code>
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Constraint fields:</strong>
            <code>minimum</code>, <code>maximum</code>, <code>exclusiveMinimum</code>, <code>exclusiveMaximum</code>, <code>minLength</code>, <code>maxLength</code>, <code>pattern</code>, <code>minItems</code>, <code>maxItems</code>, <code>uniqueItems</code>, <code>minProperties</code>, <code>maxProperties</code>
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>OpenAPI locations:</strong>
            <code>components.schemas</code>, inline parameter schemas, request body schemas, response bodies, header schemas, and any reusable schema fragments.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="correct-http-methods">
        <title>Correct <em>HTTP Methods</em></title>
        <p><strong>Improves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Agent Usability, Safety, Idempotency Guarantees</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Where...</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Operation verbs:</strong>
            map semantics to methods correctly:
            <code>GET</code> = retrieve/list,
            <code>POST</code> = create/trigger,
            <code>PUT</code> = full replace,
            <code>PATCH</code> = partial update,
            <code>DELETE</code> = remove/revoke.
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Anti-patterns to avoid:</strong>
            state-changing <code>GET</code>,
            "action verbs" in paths that conflict with methods
            (for example <code>POST /users/{id}/update</code>).
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>OpenAPI locations:</strong>
            each HTTP method under <code>paths.&lt;path&gt;.&lt;method&gt;</code>, plus
            consistent naming in <code>operationId</code>, <code>summary</code> and path templates.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="full-use-of-examples">
        <title>Full Use of <em>&quot;Examples&quot;</em></title>
        <p><strong>Improves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Developer Experience, AI-Readiness, Agent Planning</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Where...</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Single example fields:</strong>
            <code>example</code> on Parameter, Header, Media Type,
            Request Body, Response, and JSON Schema objects.
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Multiple examples:</strong>
            <code>examples</code> on Parameter, Header, Media Type, and Link
            to illustrate variations, error cases, and edge conditions.
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>OpenAPI locations:</strong>
            <code>paths.&lt;path&gt;.&lt;method&gt;.parameters[].example(s)</code>,
            <code>requestBody.content[*].example(s)</code>,
            <code>responses[status].content[*].example(s)</code>,
            <code>components.schemas.*.example</code>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="problem-details">
        <title>Use <em>RFC 9457</em> <em>Problem Details</em> for Errors</title>
        <p><strong>Improves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Error Consistency, Security Signalling, AI Error Reasoning</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Where...</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Standard error schema:</strong>
            define a reusable <code>ProblemDetails</code> in
            <code>components.schemas</code> following <strong>RFC 9457</strong>
            (for example <code>type</code>, <code>title</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>detail</code>, <code>instance</code>, plus extension members).
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Error responses:</strong>
            reference the shared schema from
            <code>responses[4xx/5xx].content['application/problem+json'].schema</code>
            and optionally the <code>default</code> response.
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>AI benefit:</strong>
            predictable error shapes make it easier for agents to detect,
            classify, and recover from failures programmatically.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="http-status-codes">
        <title>Appropriate HTTP <em>Status Code</em> Usage</title>
        <p><strong>Improves:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Foundational Compliance, Agent Usability, Observability</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Where...</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Success responses:</strong>
            use correct 2xx codes:
            <code>200</code> for successful retrieval,
            <code>201</code> for created resources,
            <code>202</code> for accepted/async,
            <code>204</code> for no-content updates or deletes.
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>Error responses:</strong>
            model common 4xx/5xx codes with schemas:
            <code>400</code>, <code>401</code>, <code>403</code>,
            <code>404</code>, <code>409</code>, <code>422</code>, <code>500</code>, ...
            not just a single generic <code>200</code> or <code>500</code>.
          </li>
          <li style="font-family: monospace">
            <strong>OpenAPI locations:</strong>
            <code>paths.&lt;path&gt;.&lt;method&gt;.responses[status]</code>
            with appropriate <code>content</code>, schema and examples per status code.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>

